847 is looking to teach members how to use CAD this summer. We don’t currently manufacture many (or really any) custom parts via printing at the moment and we do not have any advanced machining capabilities. PHRED is attempting to fundraise and acquire a CNC router this off-season and so our ability to make more complex parts will increase. Additionally, we want to give our students a greater design capacity than they would need for our team. Essentially, we want to give our them practice with a wide variety of CAD tools.

With that in mind, I’m asking all of you to share custom parts that your team uses that you think would help in the practice and development of CAD skills of our students. Tech-drawing, onshape link, or step, all contributions (as well as any suggestions) would be greatly appreciated.

Rufus ~ 847 Design Mentor

For pure CAD (not FRC-specific parts) practice you can take a look at CAD Certification Practice Exams. They’re complex parts that can be a challenge to CAD. Your mileage may vary on how CNC-able these parts are from part to part.

As a bonus, this prepares your students to get one of these certifications, if they wish. Getting CSWP is something which has been extremely helpful for me, and by getting your students certified, you’re doing them a great service.

(The Practice Exams I linked I found through a quick google search of CSWA/CSWP practice tests. I’m sure you can find something similar for your CAD program of choice)

Another option on top of all of the amazing resources people have given so far, in terms of getting the students used to CAD would be to CAD this years robot. That way you get a good grasp on how to use the software while having something physical already in hand that you can be using for things like measurements. Once you have that foundation in place you could then move on to some of the other resources mentioned here that talk about designing parts for CAM and machining on a CNC.

Something that we are doing this year is we will be having students design their own custom coins/tokens that can be 3-D printed. We also just recently purchased and received our own CNC. I am currently planning on having team members design fun SWARM themed cut outs that would help them learn more about CADD and the CNC process. I’m not sure what I’ll have our team do yet but it could be anything from keychains to robot parts. I would also look at what team 1678 has in the line of their training resources, I always find them helpful.
Hope this helps!

Can’t recommend this one enough. On top Onshape’s basics course, top-down design course changed our teams lives. It teaches good techniques and workflows and in my opinion is a must.

Also, try to CAD preexisting robots. CAD releases are a good place to start. Here is a great list by Spectrum 3847.

Finally, special mention to an incredible robot, where every single subsystem is complex and cool: FRC 254’s 2019 bot. That thing had an elevator, pivoting arm, pneumatic claws, ALL on a turret. Just check it out and see what you guys can try to replicate.
